cs.CV, cs.NE, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.HC 

Reasoning: The paper discusses a large-scale psychophysics study that assesses the correlation between computational models and human participants on a rapid animal vs. non-animal categorization task. The study analyzes the output of different stages of processing in three state-of-the-art deep networks and investigates the complexity of visual representations used by human participants during rapid categorization. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper also discusses the use of deep hierarchical architectures and their relationship to human visual decisions, which suggests possible sub-categories of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper discusses the efficiency of the visual system and the underlying brain processes, which suggests possible sub-categories of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction).
